  "taskId": "task_1778001329559_335",
  "requestedModel": "anti-claude-sonnet-4.6-thinking",
  "text": "<file_operations>\n[\n  {\n    \"action\": \"write\",\n    \"type\": \"output\",\n    \"path\": \"src/resource-management/resource-manager.service.ts\",\n    \"content\": \"import { Injectable, Logger, HttpException, HttpStatus } from '@nestjs/common';\\n\\n// Mock resource lock management for demonstration. In a real distributed system,\\n// this would be replaced by a distributed lock manager like Redis (e.g., using Redlock).\\nconst resourceLocks = new Map<string, string>(); // resourceId -> agentId\\n\\n@Injectable()\\nexport class ResourceManagerService {\\n  private readonly logger = new Logger(ResourceManagerService.name);\\n\\n  // Configuration constants should be externalized to a config file or environment variables.\\n  private readonly MAX_RETRIES = 5;\\n  private readonly INITIAL_BACKOFF_MS = 100;\\n  private readonly TIMEOUT_MS = 30000; // 30 seconds\\n\\n  /**\\n   * Simulates acquiring a resource lock.\\n   * @param resourceId The ID of the resource to lock.\\n   * @param agentId The ID of the agent requesting the lock.\\n   * @returns boolean - true if lock is acquired, false otherwise.\\n   */\\n  private tryAcquireLock(resourceId: string, agentId: string): boolean {\\n    if (!resourceLocks.has(resourceId)) {\\n      resourceLocks.set(resourceId, agentId);\\n      this.logger.log(`Agent [${agentId}] acquired lock for resource [${resourceId}]`);\\n      return true;\\n    }\\n    const currentHolder = resourceLocks.get(resourceId);\\n    if (currentHolder === agentId) {\\n      // Agent already holds the lock, this is an idempotent operation.\\n      this.logger.log(`Agent [${agentId}] re-confirmed lock for resource [${resourceId}]`);\\n      return true;\\n    }\\n    this.logger.warn(`Resource [${resourceId}] is currently locked by agent [${currentHolder}]`);\\n    return false;\\n  }\\n\\n  /**\\n   * Requests a resource with timeout and retry with exponential backoff.\\n   * @param resourceId The ID of the resource to request.\\n   * @param agentId The ID of the agent making the request.\\n   * @returns A promise that resolves when the resource is acquired.\\n   * @throws HttpException if the request times out or fails after all retries.\\n   */\\n  async requestResource(resourceId: string, agentId: string): Promise<void> {\\n    return new Promise(async (resolve, reject) => {\\n      let attempt = 0;\\n      let backoff = this.INITIAL_BACKOFF_MS;\\n\\n      const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {\\n        // Clean up the retry loop if it's still running\\n        controller.abort(); \\n        const holder = resourceLocks.get(resourceId) || 'unknown';\\n        reject(\\n          new HttpException(\\n            `Request for resource [${resourceId}] by agent [${agentId}] timed out after ${this.TIMEOUT_MS}ms. Resource is held by [${holder}].`,\\n            HttpStatus.REQUEST_TIMEOUT,\\n          ),\\n        );\\n      }, this.TIMEOUT_MS);\\n\\n      const controller = new AbortController();\\n      const { signal } = controller;\\n\\n      const tryRequest = async () => {\\n        if (signal.aborted) return;\\n\\n        if (this.tryAcquireLock(resourceId, agentId)) {\\n          clearTimeout(timeoutId);\\n          resolve();\\n          return;\\n        }\\n\\n        if (attempt >= this.MAX_RETRIES) {\\n          clearTimeout(timeoutId);\\n          const holder = resourceLocks.get(resourceId) || 'unknown';\\n          reject(\\n            new HttpException(\\n              `Failed to acquire resource [${resourceId}] for agent [${agentId}] after ${this.MAX_RETRIES} retries. Resource is held by [${holder}].`,\\n              HttpStatus.CONFLICT,\\n            ),\\n          );\\n          return;\\n        }\\n\\n        attempt++;\\n        const delay = backoff * Math.pow(2, attempt - 1);\\n        this.logger.log(\\n          `Agent [${agentId}] failed to acquire resource [${resourceId}]. Retrying in ${delay}ms... (Attempt ${attempt}/${this.MAX_RETRIES})`,\\n        );\\n        \\n        setTimeout(tryRequest, delay);\\n      };\\n\\n      await tryRequest();\\n    });\\n  }\\n\\n  /**\\n   * Releases a resource lock.\\n   * @param resourceId The ID of the resource to release.\\n   * @param agentId The ID of the agent releasing the lock.\\n   */\\n  releaseResource(resourceId: string, agentId: string): void {\\n    if (resourceLocks.get(resourceId) === agentId) {\\n      resourceLocks.delete(resourceId);\\n      this.logger.log(`Agent [${agentId}] released lock for resource [${resourceId}]`);\\n    } else {\\n      this.logger.warn(\\n        `Agent [${agentId}] attempted to release resource [${resourceId}] but does not hold the lock or it's already released.`,\\n      );\\n    }\\n  }\\n}\\n\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"action\": \"write\",\n    \"type\": \"output\",\n    \"path\": \"docs/architecture/deadlock-detection-system.md\",\n    \"content\": \"# Deadlock Detection System Architecture\\n\\n**Document ID**: `ARCH-DDS-001`\\n**Version**: `1.0`\\n**Author**: `DEV_BACKEND`\\n**Status**: `Draft`\\n\\n## 1. Overview\\n\\nThis document outlines the architecture for a monitoring system designed to proactively detect and report potential deadlock scenarios among MyCrew agents. This system is a direct preventative measure following incident `INC-202405-001`, where an agent deadlock caused a critical pipeline stall.\\n\\nThe primary goals are:\\n-   To provide real-time visibility into resource dependencies between agents.\\n-   To detect circular wait conditions (deadlocks) as they form.\\n-   To alert administrators immediately when a deadlock is detected.\\n-   To provide contextual information to help resolve the deadlock quickly.\\n\\n## 2. Core Concepts\\n\\n-   **Agent**: An autonomous unit of work within the MyCrew system (e.g., `dev_backend`, `dev_qa`).\\n-   **Resource**: Any entity that can only be used by one agent at a time (e.g., a database lock, a deployment environment, a specific test dataset).\\n-   **Waits-For Graph**: A directed graph where nodes represent agents. A directed edge from `Agent A` to `Agent B` signifies that `Agent A` is waiting for a resource currently held by `Agent B`.\\n-   **Deadlock**: A cycle in the Waits-For Graph. For example, `A -> B -> A`.\\n\\n## 3. System Architecture\\n\\nThe system consists of four main components that work together to capture events, build the dependency graph, and detect cycles.\\n\\n```mermaid\\ngraph TD\\n    subgraph MyCrew Agent Environment\\n        A[Agent A] -- 1. requests resource X --> RM(Resource Manager)\\n        RM -- 2. grants resource X --> A\\n        B[Agent B] -- 3. requests resource X --> RM\\n        RM -- 4. denies, B starts waiting --> B\\n    end\\n\\n    subgraph Deadlock Detection System\\n        EC(Event Collector)\\n        GB(Graph Builder)\\n        CD(Cycle Detector)\\n        AM(Alerting & Mitigation)\\n    end\\n\\n    RM -- 5. emits events --> Kafka(Event Stream)\\n    Kafka --> EC\\n    EC -- Parsed Events --> GB\\n    GB -- Updates Graph --> DG[(\\\"Waits-For Graph <br/> (In-Memory/Graph DB)\\\")]\\n    CD -- 6. Periodically Scans --> DG\\n    CD -- Cycle Found! --> AM\\n    AM -- Sends Alert --> Ops(Admin/Ops Team)\\n```\\n\\n## 4. Component Breakdown\\n\\n### 4.1. Event Collector\\n-   **Responsibility**: Listens for resource-related events from the `Resource Manager` or other parts of the MyCrew system.\\n-   **Events to Capture**:\\n    -   `RESOURCE_REQUESTED(agentId, resourceId, taskId)`\\n    -   `RESOURCE_ACQUIRED(agentId, resourceId, taskId)`\\n    -   `RESOURCE_RELEASED(agentId, resourceId, taskId)`\\n    -   `REQUEST_WAITING(waitingAgentId, resourceId, holdingAgentId, taskId)`\\n-   **Technology**: Subscribes to a message bus like Apache Kafka or Redis Pub/Sub to decouple it from the main application logic.\\n\\n### 4.2. Graph Builder\\n-   **Responsibility**: Maintains the real-time state of the Waits-For Graph based on the events received from the Collector.\\n-   **Logic**:\\n    -   On `REQUEST_WAITING`: Adds a directed edge from `waitingAgentId` to `holdingAgentId`.\\n    -   On `RESOURCE_ACQUIRED` (by the waiting agent) or `RESOURCE_RELEASED` (by the holding agent): Removes the corresponding edge from the graph.\\n-   **Technology**:\\n    -   **MVP**: An in-memory graph data structure (e.g., using a library like `js-graph-algorithms`).\\n    -   **Production**: A dedicated graph database like Neo4j for persistence, advanced querying, and visualization capabilities.\\n\\n### 4.3. Cycle Detection Engine\\n-   **Responsibility**: Periodically traverses the Waits-For Graph to detect cycles.\\n-   **Logic**:\\n    -   Runs on a fixed schedule (e.g., every 5 seconds).\\n    -   Uses a standard graph traversal algorithm, such as Depth-First Search (DFS), to find back edges, which indicate a cycle.\\n    -   If a cycle is found, it logs the agents and resources involved.\\n-   **Implementation**: A scheduled job (e.g., a CronJob in Kubernetes or a `setInterval` in a long-running Node.js process).\\n\\n### 4.4. Alerting & Mitigation Module\\n-   **Responsibility**: Takes action when the Cycle Detector reports a deadlock.\\n-   **Actions**:\\n    -   **Alerting (Primary)**: Sends a detailed alert to a designated channel (e.g., Slack, PagerDuty, email) containing:\\n        -   The agents involved in the deadlock.\\n        -   The resources they are waiting for.\\n        -   The associated Task IDs.\\n        -   A timestamp.\\n    -   **Automated Mitigation (Optional/Future)**: Could be configured to automatically resolve the deadlock by picking a \\\"victim\\\" task to abort based on predefined rules (e.g., lowest priority, shortest runtime). This is a high-risk action and should be implemented with caution.\\n\\n## 5. Data Flow\\n1.  An **Agent** interacts with the **Resource Manager** to request or release a resource.\\n2.  The **Resource Manager** emits events describing these interactions to an **Event Stream** (e.g., Kafka).\\n3.  The **Event Collector** consumes these events.\\n4.  The **Graph Builder** processes the events to update the **Waits-For Graph** in real-time.\\n5.  The **Cycle Detector** runs periodically, scanning the graph for cycles.\\n6.  If a cycle is detected, the **Alerting Module** is triggered, notifying the operations team.\\n\\n## 6. Next Steps\\n-   Develop a proof-of-concept for the Event Emitter within the existing `ResourceManagerService`.\\n-   Implement the MVP version of the Graph Builder and Cycle Detector as a separate microservice.\\n-   Integrate with a Slack webhook for basic alerting.\\n\"\n  }\n]\n</file_operations>\n<review_request>\n{\n  \"title\": \"[리뷰] INC-202405-001 후속 조치: 타임아웃/재시도 로직 및 교착상태 감지 아키텍처\",\n  \"assignee\": \"dev_advisor\",\n  \"message\": \"인시던트 리포트 INC-202405-001의 후속 조치를 완료했습니다.\\n\\n1.  **타임아웃 및 재시도 로직 구현**: `resource-manager.service.ts`에 에이전트 간 자원 요청 시 타임아웃과 Exponential Backoff를 적용한 재시도 로직을 구현했습니다. NestJS 서비스 형태로 작성되었으며, 분산 환경을 고려하여 향후 Redis 기반 분산 락으로 확장 가능하도록 설계했습니다.\\n\\n2.  **교착 상태 감지 시스템 아키텍처 설계**: `deadlock-detection-system.md`에 자원 의존성 그래프를 분석하여 잠재적 교착 상태를 감지하는 모니터링 시스템 아키텍처를 설계했습니다. 이벤트 기반으로 동작하며, 실시간으로 Waits-For Graph를 구성하고 주기적으로 사이클을 검사하여 교착 상태를 탐지하는 구조입니다.\\n\\n코드와 아키텍처 설계안에 대한 검토 부탁드립니다.\"\n}\n</review_request>",
